__data__.text: For centuries, the main cattle market for London was held at Smithfield.
There was no refrigeration, so butchers bought an animal at the market and slaughtered it themselves.
By the Victorian era, the volume of trade at Smithfield had increased, making it badly overcrowded and a public health nuisance.
Driving cattle to Smithfield through the thoroughfares of the metropolis was bad for traffic congestion and endangered life and limb.
In 1855, Parliament moved London's livestock market to a site in Islington called the Metropolitan Cattle Market.
Smithfield was later rebuilt as a dead meat market.
A growing population and increasing money wages created a demand for more meat.
The British farming industry could not satisfy the demand for meat.
In 1842-6, the Conservative government of Sir Robert Peel allowed all foreign cattle to be imported duty free.
The Metropolitan Cattle Market received livestock from most parts of Great Britain, Ireland, and the Continent by railway.
John Gamgee, a veterinary scientist, warned that free trade in animals was dangerous because it would import diseases.
The cattle plague epidemic of 1865-7 was the most dramatic event in 19th century agricultural history.
The Archbishop of Canterbury believed the cattle plague was a divine retribution for the sins of society.
It took two years to eradicate the cattle plague in Great Britain.
Quarantines and the mass slaughter of infected herds led to agitation against the foreign cattle trade.
Charles Dickens suggested a market exclusively reserved for foreign fat cattle at every port of debarkation.
Every animal intended for the butcher should be slain, after sale, in abbatoirs provided for the purpose.
New laws followed, encouraging the City of London to open and run a second metropolitan livestock market exclusively for imported animals.
The new market was to be known as the Foreign Cattle Market.
The new market was to operate under quarantine conditions.
No animal was to leave
The royal dockyard at Deptford, located in London, was eventually chosen for a specific purpose.
In the past, Queen Elizabeth I had come to the Deptford site to knight Francis Drake aboard the Golden Hind.
Peter the Great of Russia had studied shipbuilding at the Deptford site.
The Deptford site comprised 22 acres (8.9 ha), which was later increased to 30 acres (12 ha).
The Deptford site had a river frontage of 1,012 feet (308 m).
The Deptford site was situated on a bend in the Thames, at the bottom of Limehouse Reach.
The Deptford site was designed to receive up to three cattle boats at once.
Three large, immensely strong, timber piers were constructed for disembarking cattle.
Piers were provided with platforms at two levels, so that animals could be discharged no matter what the state of the tide.
At low tides, the water depth was at least 12 feet (3.7 m).
These piers still stand today, though they have been interconnected.
The architect of the site was Sir Horace Jones.
Sir Horace Jones also designed Smithfield Market and Tower Bridge.
Time was short, so Jones took a minimalist approach.
The existing dockyard buildings were preserved and adapted as necessary.
The dockyard had a tidal basin surrounded by three ship-building sheds.
Each shed was as lofty as Charing Cross station.
By connecting these together, Jones obtained a cattle lairage building.
The cattle lairage building comprised a pentagonal horseshoe with open sides facing the river and the landing piers.
To the east, another lairage shed had its own pier.
Animals were provided with water troughs and hay racks.
The lairs were brilliantly lighted at night by gas lamps.
There was enough covered accommodation for 5,000 cattle and 14,000 sheep.
Slaughtermen killed and butchered animals for buyers within 10 days required by law.
Buyers took away the meat, offal, hides, and fleeces, most of which they resold at Smithfield.
In 1887, 9.4 million animals had been landed at Deptford.
The volume of trade fluctuated, but it increased from modest beginnings in 1872.
By about 1890, more foreign cattle were sent to Deptford than British cattle to Islington.
By 1907, 78% of London's live cattle trade went to Deptford.
The largest number of cattle ever landed in one year was 224,831 (1897), and of sheep, 783,440 (1882).
In the Edwardian era, Chicago meatpackers bypassed the marketing system by taking advantage of a loophole in the regulations.
A combination of Chicago meatpackers took advantage of the loophole in the regulations by not putting animals up for sale on market days.
Altogether, 16.5 million animals were slaughtered at Deptford.
Cattle boats from the Continent came up the Thames on Sundays and Wednesdays.
Over a thousand cattle boats from the Continent came up the Thames annually.
Three paddle steamers, named Racoon, Taurus, and Claude Hamilton, were purchased by the market.
Between them, the three vessels conveyed more than 1.6 million animals to Deptford.
One theory about Jack the Ripper was that he was a Portuguese cattle attendant on a boat from Porto.
A customs official claimed to see a statistical correlation between the arrival of cattle boats and Whitechapel murders.
The Queen feared that the Detective Department was not as efficient as it might be.
The Queen asked if the cattle boats and passenger boats had been examined.
On landing, animals were examined by a veterinary surgeon who took their pulse and temperature.
Suspect animals were set aside for observation.
The City interviewed 25 candidates for the position of superintendent at the market.
George Philcox, a 28-year old Southend station-master, was chosen as the superintendent for the market.
Philcox was in charge of the market for the next 40 years.
When Philcox died in 1912, the market soon closed.
Philcox was an able and popular man.
The market employed about 110 direct employees.
In addition to the direct employees, 1500 casual workers were employed, mostly as drovers and slaughtermen.
The casual workers were paid on piecework.
The hours of work for the casual workers were irregular.
Employment for the casual workers was precarious due to changing animal disease regulations.
There was much insobriety among the high-wage, insecure jobs that attracted improvident men.
Unemployment at the market could cause severe hardship in Deptford.
Market workers sent a wreath to the funeral of George Joseph Cooper MP, who had tried to get Argentina removed from the blacklist.
Efforts were made in 1924 to re-open the market, even after it had closed.
Drovers were responsible for driving animals off the boats or transshipping them from transatlantic steamers.
Nearly all drovers began their life in the market as "ochre boys".
Drovers were paid a lump sum per vessel.
A cattle boat could be unloaded in as little as 15 minutes.
Some cattle, especially from Argentina, were very wild.
A man in regular employment could earn as much as £4 a week.
Slaughtermen killed and butchered the animals.
Slaughtermen worked in gangs of four.
Slaughtermen earned very high wages for the era.
No slaughtering was done on Saturdays.
The work of slaughtermen was brutalising and conducive to drink.

A job in Deptford market involved cleaning cattle and sheep intestines, which were used for making sausage skins and, according to a later source, condoms.
Originally, men did this work. In about 1891, they went on strike for more pay.
Management responded by assigning the work to women.
Around 80-100 women and girls, aged 14 to 40, were employed daily.
They worked for two firms that had contracted to buy all the gut offal from the market's slaughterhouses.
A lady visitor, who claimed to have smelled some vile odors in her time, found the stink insupportable.
Men coarsely de-fatted tubs of unwashed entrails.
The women's share in the work began when the greasy, slimy intestinal skins came to them for scraping off all fat and substance still attaching to them.
A first group of women cleaned the outside of the intestines, made them into a figure of eight rope, and tossed them to a second group.
The second group, armed with a powerful watercock, turned the gut inside out and washed it ready for the sausage makers.
In winter, the water nearly froze the hands of the women.
They made 12s to 14s (≅ £77 to £892018) a week, which, for women's work, was good pay.
Queen Victoria took an interest in the Deptford market.
She asked her daughter-in-law, the Duchess of Albany, to look into the working conditions of the girls there.
The Duchess of Albany went down to Deptford, saw the work, was horrified, and complained in high places.
The gut firms had been processing, not just the entrails from Deptford market, but huge quantities brought in from outside.
The City's markets committee banned this as a health risk.
The women became unemployed.

Forrest Capie and Richard Perren stated that most European animals were shipped from Rotterdam and Hamburg.

Rotterdam and Hamburg were terminal stations of a great network of main German railway lines and branch lines that ran into Hungary, Poland, and Galicia and extended right up to the Bessarabian frontier.
In the 1860s, the Dutch ports alone sent 150,000 cattle and 250,000 sheep to Britain.
Many of the cattle and sheep passed through the markets of Austria and several German principalities before they reached their port of embarkation.
Several Deptford shipments arrived directly from the port of Kronstadt, in Russia.
These animals were purchased in the cattle market of Saint Petersburg.
Saint Petersburg was more than 30° to the east of Deptford.
The Russian capital raised few export-grade cattle.
The animals may have been driven to market from south Russia.
In 1872, the Russian Empire was blacklisted for cattle plague and no more Russian cattle could be landed, even at Deptford.
The European livestock trade was gradually stopped by the late 1880s, except for Iceland.
The British authorities faced the fact that too much livestock was really coming from places where disease was endemic.
The provincial authorities made no attempt to stamp out the disease.
Prussia had stringent laws against animal disease.
The profits from smuggling cattle from Poland were too enticing.
By then, the United States had become the main supplier of livestock to Deptford market.
Of all the cattle ever landed at Deptford market, the largest proportion came from the U.S.A.
Nearly all American livestock exports went to England.
Americans sent livestock to England because they had a surplus that could not be absorbed by local demand.
When, eventually, local demand was able to absorb the surplus, exportation ceased.
The surplus came from the new, teeming lands of the American West.
In 1884, 95% of cattle exported to other countries came from the Western part of the United States.
In 1880, a 1,200 pounds (540 kg) steer from Colorado, Wyoming, or Montana could be transported to Deptford market for £10 or £12.
This cost included cowboys' wages, rail fare, shipping freight, and landing charges at Deptford.
The additional cost for transportation was 4d a pound, which is equivalent to £4.40 a kilo in 2018.
In the past, five cattle-laden steamers sailed from New York to England in one day.
Cattle in this new trade came from Ohio, Kentucky, Illinois, Iowa, Missouri, Kansas, Nebraska, Colorado, and sometimes even as far as Oregon.
In 1884, a ship called Croma, which was due at Deptford on Saturday, the 25th, had on board a hundred fat bullocks.
These bullocks were the first consignment of western American cattle to take advantage of the cheap transportation afforded by the Great Lakes.
Majority of the cattle were bred by the author and his brother in Wyoming in 1881.
Some of the cattle were from far distant Oregon and had walked through from there to Wyoming in 1882.
These cattle from Oregon were purchased by the author at the end of their long march.
It is remarkable that cattle calved more than 6,000 miles away on the shores of the Pacific Ocean, matured in Wyoming, and fattened on Lake Superior, were destined to be slaughtered in the Thames.
The exportation of cattle to England had a significant impact on the American livestock industry.
London was the most important market for American exports.

The impact of foreign demand for U.S. meat was reflected in the growth of the Western packinghouse industry, the expansion of railway traffic due to the movement of live and butchered animals, and the growth of livestock herds.
The trade became a factor
The Argentine cattle industry initially supplied inferior breeds of cattle, mainly used for their hides, bones, and tallow.
Selective breeding and alfalfa forage improved the quality of the Argentine cattle, transforming the country into a major exporter of beef.
Live cattle and sheep were shipped from Buenos Aires to Deptford, traveling by rail and steam crane.
The voyage from Buenos Aires to London took approximately 30 days.
Argentine cattlemen recognized the importance of quality and paid large sums for Shorthorn bulls to enhance their herds.
In 1903, it was challenging to acquire high-quality beef in Buenos Aires due to demand for export-grade cattle.
"Wild, untamed brutes" required taming and training to eat hay for long sea journeys.
Deptford closed to Argentine cattle and sheep in 1900 due to foot-and-mouth disease and reopened briefly in 1903.
After 1900, good chilled Argentine beef became a more appealing alternative, leading to unemployment in Deptford.
Cattle and sheep were shipped from Victoria (Australia), New South Wales, Queensland, and Dunedin (New Zealand) to Deptford Market.
The first commercial (experimental) shipment from Sydney to Deptford on the steamer Maori King took 67 days and resulted in a heavy loss.
A more successful voyage was achieved by Port Pirie in 1895, with only one animal dying of heat in the Red Sea.
The Angers shipment of 381 cattle from Gladstone, Queensland, resulted in 32 surviving animals, some of which were maimed.
The Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals intervened, and the Board of Agriculture prohibited the Angers from carrying live stock for a year.
In the Australasian live trade, 607 cattle and 57 sheep were lost out of 2,654 and 3,882 shipped, respectively.

C.W. Bowerman was a Labour MP for Deptford.
Winston Churchill was the President of the Board of Trade.
Bowerman questioned Churchill persistently.
The questioning by Bowerman led to an inquiry into the control of the meat supply, distribution, and price in the United Kingdom.
The inquiry was set up by Churchill.
The inquiry reported in 1909.
The allegations of Bowerman were generally true.
The Trust did not have the power to fix the price of beef in the United Kingdom.
The Trust controlled the North Atlantic meat trade.
American beef exports had declined.
Large shipments of refrigerated beef were coming from Argentina.
Animal welfare is a consideration in modern times.
The average journey from feedlot to slaughter plant lasts just a few hours in modern times.
Transport-related stress and injury are major sources of loss to the American meat industry.
Fear is a strong stressor during transport for animals.
Animals unaccustomed to human beings are liable to be stressed more.
In the Victorian era, there was publicity about the iniquities of transatlantic cattle ships.
Most animals had endured journeys in cattle trains before crossing the Atlantic.
The train journeys were as bad as the sea voyages if not worse.
American cattle most often sailed from New York.
Canadian cattle were shipped from the port of Montreal.
Argentine cattle and sheep were shipped from the port of Buenos Aires.
Sending cattle safely across the Atlantic demanded forward planning and knowhow.
Conditions were very bad or little better than the horrors of the old slave trading days in the early days of transatlantic cattle shipping.
The worst culprits were tramp steamers.
These vessels were hastily rigged up with temporary decks and crammed tightly with cattle.
Risk was greatest in winter.
Insurance rates soared to 10% in winter.
A heavy storm may make it necessary to lighten the ship by
Cattle ships were reported to be dangerously unstable in stormy weather.
Cattle were carried on the upper deck or on a temporary, higher platform in cattle ships.
The Erin, a cattle ship, sailed from New York to London in December 1889 with 527 cattle and 74 men on board. The Erin has not been heard of since then.
Plimsoll claimed that animals were washed overboard by heavy seas or deliberately jettisoned to save the vessel.
Animals could stifle to death after the hatches were battened down in bad weather.
Plimsoll alleged that captains sometimes took risks in leaving the hatches open.
Animals stood on their own dung, which could not be cleared away.
Animals fell about helplessly and were injured, often fatally, on the slippery surface.
Plimsoll claimed that cattle attendants were not allowed to euthanise badly injured livestock.
Plimsoll alleged that animals were left to die a lingering death.
Plimsoll probably wrongly accused insurance companies of refusing to pay up if cattle attendants euthanised badly injured livestock.

Cattle attendants used cruel methods to make animals get on their feet, such as piercing them with pitchforks, twisting their tails, beating them about the head with iron buckets, or pouring paraffin in their ears.
Cattle shippers denied using cruel methods to make animals stand up.
Cattle attendants included foremen known as "cowboys of the seas" and a despised class called "stiffs".
"Stiffs" worked for little or no pay just to get across the Atlantic.
Educated men, such as Harvard students, travelled as stiffs.
The poet W.H. Davies was a stiff and wrote about the harsh methods used to make the cattle stand up.
An English solicitor returning from a working holiday to Canada also wrote about the harsh methods used to make the cattle stand up.
The harsh methods were used to stop animals tangling their head ropes or being trampled to death by their fellows
Cattle being transported on ships from New York to the Thames often have seawater freeze on their backs.
Heavy rolls and pitches on ships can cause broken legs for cattle.
The average run from New York to the Thames takes 11 days.
Cattle have the ability to scent land and will sometimes set up a "united bellow" when they are 30 to 40 hours from shore.
In the United States, cattle are taken to market by train, mostly to Chicago.
Seventeen railroads converge at the Chicago stockyards.
There is a special market at the Chicago stockyards for "export grade" cattle.
These "export grade" cattle are railed to ports on the eastern seaboard for shipment to England.
The Canadian Pacific Railway transports livestock from the foothills of the Rocky mountains to Montreal.
Animals are not supposed to travel more than 28 hours at a time, according to a U.S. federal law from 1873.
After 28 hours of travel, animals must be given water, food, and 5 hours of rest.
Railroad companies often neglected to provide proper water, food, or rest for the animals during required rest stops.
In 1906, the law was amended to allow animals to be carried for up to 36 hours at a time if the owners agreed.
"Palace" or "parlor" stock cars are special vehicles that are supposed to provide water and hay for animals.
These special vehicles are exempt from the 28-hour law and can run for 60 or even 100 hours at a time.
Water and food are seldom supplied to these special vehicles.
Shipping space is usually sold by the carload, which creates an incentive to cram in as many animals as possible to save freight charges.
Tight packing of animals is thought by some to be good for them because it stops them from fighting or lying down.
If a steer falls down or lies down to rest, there is a risk that it might never get up again.

A government official made a statement about the condition of cattle transported by train to market under the present system. The official observed that many cattle arrived crippled and several were dead.
The statement was made in the context of Canada, which did not have a 28-hour law and where rail journeys for cattle were long.
The Canadian Live Stock Commissioner described the method of exporting western range cattle as "sinfully wasteful, unbusinesslike and unprofitable to the producer".
The Commissioner stated that Canadian cattle arrived in Britain "gaunt and shrunken".
Samuel Plimsoll argued that the transatlantic cattle trade had no rational commercial purpose except to enrich dishonest traders.
Plimsoll questioned why live cattle were imported at all when their beef could be more cheaply and easily imported, and in better condition.
Plimsoll stated that middlemen could add to their legitimate profit an illegitimate one by calling live cattle "best Scotch", "town-killed", or "English-fed" beef.
This could not be done if the beef were imported dead.
An alternative to the live cattle trade was American chilled meat.
American chilled meat was already being imported into London in 1875, before the Foreign Cattle Market was doing much business, and it was a commercial success.
It was much cheaper to send meat across the Atlantic chilled than on the hoof.
Refrigerating plant was required, but chilled meat took up less space and only the edible parts were shipped.
Butchers could easily tell that wholesale meat was American if it was imported dead, but not if it was imported alive.
Meat slaughtered in America was cut ("dressed") according to American butchering practices, which were visibly different.
The chilling process slightly discolored the product.
In contrast, American meat killed at Deptford was dressed by British butchers, hence looked the same as British-fed beef.
At Smithfield Market, a wholesale quantity of Deptford-killed American beef sold for 10-15% more than the same weight of American chilled beef.
This price premium
Plimsoll argued that it was up to the customer to decide whether to pay more for British-grown beef.
Plimsoll believed that if a customer was willing to pay more for British-grown beef, they were entitled to get the real thing.
Richard Perren of Aberdeen University wrote an essay in 1971 that argued the live meat trade survived because the chilled meat trade was riskier.
Perren acknowledged that some butchers fraudulently sold Deptford-killed meat as English, with the price being higher.
Incentives to fraud existed in the meat trade.
Effective compulsory marking of origin was not introduced until 1933.
Plimsoll calculated that the fraud was worth a penny the pound of meat, or £4 per head of cattle (≝ £5002018).
A 2010 study found that substantial incentives existed to misrepresent American beef as Scottish/English.
The gains from misrepresenting American beef as Scottish/English declined over time and had ceased to exist by 1911.
In the Victorian era, foreign merino sheep were slaughtered at Deptford, sent to Cardiff, the hind quarters there cut off, sent to London again, and there sold as Welsh mutton.

Scientific American reported in 1904 that the strong and abiding prejudice of the Englishman against either frozen or chilled meat, or imported meat of any sort if he knows it to be imported, can be overcome in only one way.
Instead of carcasses chilled or frozen being brought, the live cattle are conveyed to an English port and at once taken ashore and slaughtered.
An expert would find it hard to tell the difference between live cattle slaughtered in England and imported cattle.
A writer for a Chicago livestock magazine in 1912 tried and failed to find any American meat for sale at Smithfield.
At last a stallholder admitted that American meat was being sold as English at Smithfield.
An English port medical officer remarked on the disparity between port-killed wholesale prices and butchers' retail prices
Deptford became a supply base.
The supply base sent rations to troops in France.
After the war, the City of London sold Deptford to the government.
The site where the supply base was located became known as Convoys Wharf.
Some remains of the old market and former dockyard, such as boundary walls, still stand today in Deptford.
The City within the City is a glimpse of elite formation in Deptford, London and Dadaocheng, Taipei.
